window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART I>1>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : PROFIT AND LOSS","question":"A shop keeper buys 40 kg of fruits for \u20a6120.00. He sells 20 kg at \u20a65.00 per kg. 10 kg at \u20a63.00 per kg; 5 kg at \u20a62.00 per kg and the remaining 5 kg at 50 k per kg. Calculate the:    amount he realises from the sales","images":[],"marking_scheme":"40 kg of fruits at \u20a6120.00;  Sells 20 kg at \u20a65.00 per kg ==> 20 x \u20a65.00 = \u20a6100.00  Sells 10 kg at \u20a63.00 per kg ==> 10 x \u20a63.00 = \u20a630.00  Sells 5 kg at \u20a62.00 per kg ==> 5 x \u20a62.00 = \u20a610.00  Remaining = 40 kg - (20 + 10 + 5) kg = 40 kg - 35 kg = 5 kg  \u2234 Remaining 5 kg at 50 k per kg = 5 x \u20a60.50 = \u20a62.50  Total = \u20a6100.00 + \u20a630.00 + \u20a610.00 + \u20a62.50 = \u20a6142.50  \u2234 amount he realises from the sales is \u20a6142.50","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART I>1>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : PROFIT AND LOSS","question":"A shop keeper buys 40 kg of fruits for \u20a6120.00. He sells 20 kg at \u20a65.00 per kg. 10 kg at \u20a63.00 per kg; 5 kg at \u20a62.00 per kg and the remaining 5 kg at 50 k per kg. Calculate the:  total profit","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Total profit = Amount realised from sale - Cost of fruits = \u20a6142.50 - \u20a6120.00  \u2234 Total profit = \u20a622.50","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART I>1>c","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : PERCENTAGES","question":"A shop keeper buys 40 kg of fruits for \u20a6120.00. He sells 20 kg at \u20a65.00 per kg. 10 kg at \u20a63.00 per kg; 5 kg at \u20a62.00 per kg and the remaining 5 kg at 50 k per kg. Calculate the:  percentage profit on his outlay of \u20a6120.00","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Profit on outlay = \u20a622.50  \u2234Percentageprofit=profitcost of fruitsx100%=22.5120x100%=18.75%","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART I>2>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : SIMULTANEOUS LINEAR EQUATIONS IN TWO VARIABLES","question":"Solve the simultaneous equations: 6y + 5x = -12; 4y - 3x = 11","images":[],"marking_scheme":"6y + 5x = -12 ----- eqn (i)  4y - 3x = 11 ----- eqn (ii)  To eliminate x, multiply eqn. (i) by 3 and eqn. (ii) by 5.  18y + 15x = -36  20y - 15x = 55 (Add)  38y = 19  y = 19/38 = 1/2  Substitute value for y in eqn. (ii)  4(1/2)  - 3x = 11  2 - 3x = 11  2 - 11 = 3x  -9 = 3x  x = -9/3 = -3","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART I>2>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : LENGTHS AND PERIMETERS","question":"In the diagram below, ADC is a straight line. |CD| = 48 cm, |BD| = 36 cm and |AD| = y cm. Find the value of y.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"By pythagoras theorem:  |BD|2 + |DC|2 = |BC|2  362 + 482 = |BC|2  1296 + 2304 = |BC|2  3600 = |BC|2  |BC| = \u221a3600  |BC| = 60 cm  But \u2206s BCD || ABD (RHS)  \u2234BDDC=ADBD==>3648=y36  \u2234 48y = 1296  \u2234 y = 27 cm","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART I>3>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"The table below shows the marks obtained by forty pupils in a mathematics test:  Marks0-910-1920-2930-3940-4950-59No of pupils4561285    Draw a histogram  for the mark distribution.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART I>3>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"The table below shows the marks obtained by forty pupils in a mathematics test:  Marks0-910-1920-2930-3940-4950-59No of pupils4561285Use your histogram to estimate the mode","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Mode = 35.5","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART I>3>c","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"The table below shows the marks obtained by forty pupils in a mathematics test:  Marks0-910-1920-2930-3940-4950-59No of pupils4561285Calculate the median of the distribution.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Median=L+ ((N/2 - F)fm)h  N = Total no of observers ==> sum of freq. ==> 40  L = Lower class boundary of median class ==> 29.5  F = Sum of all freq. below L = 15  fm = Frequency of median class = 12  h = Class width of median class = 10    \u2234Median=29.5+ ((40/2 - 15)12)10  =29.5+ ((20 - 15)12)10  =29.5+ (512)10  = 29.5 + 4.17  = 33.67","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART I>4>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : LOGARITHMS","question":"If log102 = 0.3010 and log103 = 0.4771, calculate without using the tables the value of log100.72.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"log100.72 = log10(72/100)    = log1072 - log10100 = log10(23 x 32) - log10102    = log1023 + log1032 - log10102    = 3log102 + 2log103 - 2log1010    = 3(0.3010) + 2(0.4771) - 2(1) (Recall that logaa = 1)    = 0.9030 + 0.9542 - 2    = 1.8572 - 2 ==> -0.1428 or 1.8572","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART I>4>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"TRIGONOMETRY : ANGLES OF ELEVATION AND DEPRESSION","question":"A hawk on top of a tree, 20 metres high, views a chick on the ground at an angle of depression of 39o, find, correct to 2 significant figures the distance of the chick from the bottom of the tree.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"39o = Angle of depression  (\u03b1 + 39)o = 90o (complimentary angle)  \u03b1 = 90o - 39o = 51o  tan\u03b1=BCHB  tan51o=BC20==>20tan51o=BC  Distance of chick from base of tree = 20 x 1.2349 = 24.69 m  = 25 m (2 s.f)","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART I>5>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : ANGLES","question":"ABCD is a trapezium with AB parallel to DC and |AD| = |AB|. If \u2220BAD = 106o, find \u2220BDC.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Given the trapezium;  \u2206DAB = isoceles (AB = AD)  \u2234 If BDC = \u03b1 \u2234 ABD = \u03b1  ==> \u03b1 + 106o + \u03b1 = 180o (angles of a \u2206)  2\u03b1 = 180o - 106o  2\u03b1 = 74o  \u03b1 = 37o  But \u2220A + \u2220B + \u2220C + \u2220D = 360o (sum of angles of a quadrilateral)  106o + 90o + 90o + \u2220D = 360o  106o + \u2220D = 180o  \u2220D = 74o  If \u2220BDC = \u03b8  \u2234 \u03b8 + \u03b1 = 74o  \u2220DBC = 37o  \u03b8 + 37o = 74o    \u2234 \u03b8 = 37o","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART I>5>b>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : PROBABILITY","question":"The table below shows the distribution of 20 cards labelled A-E  CardABCDEFrequency34751    If a card is selected at random from the pack, what is the probability that the card is E?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Total No of cards = Sum of frequencies = 20  A card is selected at random, Pr(card selected is E) = 1/20","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART I>5>b>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : PROBABILITY","question":"The table below shows the distribution of 20 cards labelled A-E  CardABCDEFrequency34751  If two cards are selected at random one after the other without replacement from the pack, what is the probability that one of the two cards is B?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Two cards selected at random one after the other and without replacement, Pr(one of the two selected cards is B)  ==> Pr(1st B and 2nd not B) + Pr(1st not B and 2nd B)  ==> i.e Pr(1st B) x Pr(2nd not B) + Pr(1st not B) x Pr(2nd B)  ==>(420x1619)+(1620x419)=1695+1695=3295","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>6>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : FRACTIONS, DECIMALS AND APPROXIMATIONS","question":"Withoutusingtables,findthevalueof0.45 x 0.910.0117","images":[],"marking_scheme":"0.45 x 0.910.0117=4.5 x 10-1 x 9.1 x 10-11.17 x 10-2=40.95 x 10-21.17 x 10-2=40.951.17=35","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>6>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : FRACTIONS, DECIMALS AND APPROXIMATIONS","question":"Find the number which is exactly half way between 16/7 and 211/28.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Let the number which is exactly half way between 16/7 and 211/28 be x    \u2234 x - 16/7 = 211/28 - x    \u2234 2x = 211/28 + 16/7    2x=6728+137  2x=67 + 5228=11928  x=11956  \u2234 x = 21/8","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>6>c","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : ANGLES","question":"If each interior angle of a regular polygon is five times the exterior angle, how many sides has the polygon?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Given that p is the interior angle and x = exterior angle, then p = 5x  But p + x = 180o  \u2234 5x + x = 180o  6x = 180o  x = 30o  \u2234 Each exterior angle of the polygon is 30o  Also the sum of all the exterior angles of a polygon is 360o.  \u2234 If the polygon has n sides ==> 30n = 360o  n=36030==>n=12.Thepolygonhas12sides.","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>6>d","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"d","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : VOLUMES","question":"Calculate the volume of the material used in making a pipe 20 cm long, with an internal diameter 6 cm and external diameter 8 cm.  [Take \u03c0 = 22/7]","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Volume of material = \u03c0R2h - \u03c0r2h; where R and r are respectively 4 cm and 3 cm.  V=\u03c0h(R2-r2)=227x20(42-32)  =227x20(16-9)==>227x20x7=440cm3","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>7>a>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : SETS","question":"The universal set U is the set of all integers. P, Q and R are subsets of U defined as follows:  P = {x: x \u2264 2}; Q = {x: -7    P \u22c2 Q","images":[],"marking_scheme":"U = {all integers}  P = {x: x \u2264 2} ==> P = {... -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2}  Q = {x: -7  Q = {-6, -5, -4, -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, ..., 11, 12, 13, 14}  R = {x: -2 \u2264 x  R = {-2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, ..., 15, 16, 17, 18}  P \u22c2 Q = {-6, -5, -4, -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2}","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>7>a>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"NUMBER AND NUMERATION : SETS","question":"The universal set U is the set of all integers. P, Q and R are subsets of U defined as follows:  P = {x: x \u2264 2}; Q = {x: -7  P \u22c2 (Q \u22c3 R1), where R1 is the complement of R with respect to U.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"R1 = {..., -5, -4, -3, 19, 20, 21, ...}  (Q \u22c3 R1) = {..., -6, -5, -4, -3, -2, 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, ..., 20, 21, ...}  \u2234 P \u22c2 (Q \u22c3 R1) = {..., -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2}","marks":"4","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>7>b>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"The following data shows the marks of 40 students in a History examination.    41 52 37 56 63 48 65 46  54 32 51 66 74 23 35 61  58 44 49 53 45 57 56 38  59 28 50 49 67 56 36 45  79 68 43 56 26 47 55 71    Form a grouped frequency table with the class intervals 20-29, 30-39, 40-49; etc","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Marks20-2930-3940-4950-5960-6970-79No of students35101363","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>7>b>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : STATISTICS","question":"The following data shows the marks of 40 students in a History examination.    41 52 37 56 63 48 65 46  54 32 51 66 74 23 35 61  58 44 49 53 45 57 56 38  59 28 50 49 67 56 36 45  79 68 43 56 26 47 55 71  Find the mean of the distribution.    [Let the assumed mean be 55.5]","images":[],"marking_scheme":"MarksFreq.Class centre (C)D = C - A.MfDfD220-29325.5-30-90270030-39535.5-20-100200040-491045.5-10-100100050-591355.500060-69665.5106060070-79375.520601200\u2211f = 40\u2211fd = -170\u2211fd2 = 7500  Let the assumed mean be 55.5  Mean(X)=Assumedmean+\u2211fd\u2211f   X=55.5+ (-17040)  \u2234  X  = 55.5 - 4.25 = 51.25","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>8>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : ALGEBRAIC FRACTIONS","question":"Find the number N such that when 1/3 of it is added to 8, the result is the same as when 1/2 of it is subtracted from 18.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"1/3N + 8 = 18 - 1/2N    1/3N + 1/2N = 18 - 8    5/6N = 10    N = 10 x 6/5    N = 2 x 6    \u2234 N = 12","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>8>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CONSTRUCTION","question":"Using a ruler and a pair of compasses only, construct a trapezium ABCD, in which the parallel sides AB and DC are 4 cm apart, \u2220DAB = 60o, |AB| = 8 cm, and |BC| = 5 cm. Measure |DC|.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"8","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>9>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : FUNCTIONS AND RELATIONS","question":"Copy and complete the table below for y = 3x2 - 5x - 7    x-3-2-101234y = 3x2 - 5x - 735-7-95","images":[],"marking_scheme":"x-3-2-101234y = 3x2 - 5x - 735151-7-9-5521    when x = -2; y = 3(-2)2 - 5(-2) - 7 = 3(4) + 10 - 7 = 12 + 3 ==> y = 15  when x = -1; y = 3(-1)2 - 5(-1) - 7 = 3(1) + 5 - 7 = 3 - 2 ==> y = 1  when x = 2; y = 3(2)2 - 5(2) - 7 = 3(4) - 10 - 7 = 12 - 17 ==> y = -5  when x = 4; y = 3(4)2 - 5(4) - 7 = 3(16) - 20 - 7 = 48 - 27 ==> y = 21","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>9>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : GRAPHS OF LINEAR AND QUADRATIC FUNCTIONS","question":"Copy and complete the table below for y = 3x2 - 5x - 7    x-3-2-101234y = 3x2 - 5x - 735-7-95Using a scale of 2 cm = 1 unit along the x-axis and 2 cm = 5 units along the y-axis, draw the graph of y = 3x2 - 5x - 7.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>9>c","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : GRAPHS OF LINEAR AND QUADRATIC FUNCTIONS","question":"Copy and complete the table below for y = 3x2 - 5x - 7    x-3-2-101234y = 3x2 - 5x - 735-7-95On the same axes draw the graph of y + 3x + 2 = 0.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Table for y = -(3x + 2) [From y + 3x + 2 = 0]    x-3-2-101234y = -(2 + 3x)741-2-5-8-11-14    when x = -3; y = -(2 + 3(-3)) = -(2 - 9) = -(-7) ==> y = 7  when x = -2; y = -(2 + 3(-2)) = -(2 - 6) = -(-4) ==> y = 4  when x = -1; y = -(2 + 3(-1)) = -(2 - 3) = -(-1) ==> y = 1  when x = 0; y = -(2 + 3(0)) = -(2 - 0) = -(2) ==> y = -2  when x = 1; y = -(2 + 3(1)) = -(2 + 3) = -(5) ==> y = -5  when x = 2; y = -(2 + 3(2)) = -(2 + 6) = -(8) ==> y = -8  when x = 3; y = -(2 + 3(3)) = -(2 + 9) = -(11) ==> y = -11  when x = 4; y = -(2 + 3(4)) = -(2 + 12) = -(14) ==> y = -14  ___________________________________________________________________________________         3x2 - 5x - 7 + 3x + 2 = y + 3x + 2 [By adding (3x + 2) to both sides]  Simplifying  ==> 3x2 - 5x + 3x - 7 + 2 = y + 3x + 2  3x2 - 2x - 5 = y + 3x + 2  ==> roots of 3x2 - 2x - 5 is the point where 3x2 - 5x - 7 equals -(2 + 3x);  i.e 3x2 - 2x - 5 -(2 + 3x) = y  \u2234 Roots of 3x2 - 2x - 5 is the point of intersection of the two graphs  \u2234 Solution as indicated on the graph is -1.0 and 1.6","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>9>d>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : LINEAR INEQUALITIES","question":"Copy and complete the table below for y = 3x2 - 5x - 7    x-3-2-101234y = 3x2 - 5x - 735-7-95  From your graph, find the:    range of values of x for which 3x2 - 5x - 7","images":[],"marking_scheme":"From the graph  3x2 - 5x - 7  Range of values of x for which 3x2 - 5x - 7 is negative is the point where the graph cuts the x-axis downward.  \u2234 Range ==> -0.9 \u2264 x \u2264 2.6","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>9>d>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : QUADRATIC EQUATIONS","question":"Copy and complete the table below for y = 3x2 - 5x - 7    x-3-2-101234y = 3x2 - 5x - 735-7-95  From your graph, find the:  roots of the equation 3x2 - 2x - 5 = 0","images":[],"marking_scheme":"3x2 - 2x - 5 = 0  Starting equation ==> 3x2 - 5x - 7 = y  3x2 - 5x - 7 + (3x + 2) = y + (3x + 2) [Add (3x + 2) to both sides]  3x2 - 2x - 5 = y + 3x + 2  ==> roots of 3x2 - 2x - 5 is the point where 3x2 - 5x - 7 equals -(2 + 3x);  i.e 3x2 - 2x - 5 -(2 + 3x) = y  \u2234 Roots of 3x2 - 2x - 5 is the point of intersection of the two graphs  \u2234 Solution as indicated on the graph is -1.0 and 1.6","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>10>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"ALGEBRAIC PROCESSES : CHANGE OF SUBJECT OF A FORMULA/RELATION","question":"Make d subject of the formula S = n/2(2a + (n - 1)d)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"S = n/2(2a + (n - 1)d)  2S = n(2a + (n - 1)d)  2S = 2an + dn(n - 1)  2S - 2an = dn(n - 1)  d=2S - 2ann(n - 1)=2(S - an)n(n - 1)","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>10>b>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : CIRCLES","question":"In the diagram above, O is the centre of the circle. A, B and P are points on the circumference. Prove that \u2220AOB = 2\u2220APB","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"To prove that \u2220AOB = 2\u2220APB   Construction:  Locate any point A on the circumference and join AXB  As shown \u2234  Proof:  OA = OB (radii)  \u2206AOB is isosceles  \u2220OAB = \u2220OBA (base angles of an isosceles \u2206)  Acute \u2220AOB = 2\u2220AXB (angle at the centre is twice angle at circumference)  \u2220AXB = 1/2\u2220AOB  But from above, \u2220AXB = \u2220APB  \u2220AXB = \u2220APB = 1/2\u2220AOB  \u2220AOB = 2\u2220AXB ==> \u2220AOB = 2\u2220APB. QED","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>10>b>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"PLANE GEOMETRY : ANGLES","question":"Find angles x, y and z in the diagram below.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The shape above is a cyclic quadrilateral since all its vertices lie on the circumference of the circle  x = 2y (angle at the centre is twice angle at the circumference)  z = 2 x 126o (angle at the centre is twice angle at the circumference)  z = 252o  But z + x = 360o (angles at a point)  252o + x = 360o ==> x = 360o - 252o = 108o  Sincex=2y\u2234108o=2y==>y=1082=54o","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>11>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"MENSURATION : LONGITUDES AND LATITUDES","question":"P and Q are points on the parallel of latitude 68.7oS, their longitudes being 124oW and 56oE respectively. What is their distance apart measured along the parallel of latitude?  [Take R = 6400 km, \u03c0 = 3.142]","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Angle PXQ = 124o + 56o = 180o  Radius of latitude 68.7oS = Rcos \u03b1 where R = 6400 km  \u03b1 = 68.7  Distancemeasuredalongtheparalleloflatitude68.7oS=\u03b8360x2\u03c0r  ==>180360x2x3.142x6400xcos68.7=7,239,168cos 68.7360=2,629,636.6836360=7,305  = 7,310 km (to 3 s.f)","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>11>b>i","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : PROBABILITY","question":"A bag contains four red, three white and five green balls.    If one ball is picked at random, what is the probability that it is not green?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"4 red balls; 3 white balls; 5 green balls  Pr(a ball picked at random is not green) = 1 - Pr(green)  Pr(green) = 5/12  \u2234 Pr(not green) = 1 - 5/12 = 7/12","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>11>b>ii","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY. : PROBABILITY","question":"A bag contains four red, three white and five green balls.  If two balls are picked at random without replacement, what is the probability that one is red, the other white?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Iftwoballsarepickedwithoutreplacement,findPr(oneredandtheotherwhite)  Theorderisnotnecessaryi.ewhether1stred,2ndwhiteor1stwhite,2ndred  \u2234Pr(oneredotherwhite)=Pr(1stred,2ndwhite)+Pr(1stwhiteand2ndred)  Pr(1stred)=412=13  Pr(2ndwhite)=311  Pr(1stred,2ndwhite)=13x311=111  Pr(1stwhite)=312=14  Pr(2ndred)=411  Pr(1stwhite,2ndred)=14x411=111  \u2234Pr(oneredotherwhite)=111+111=211","marks":"4","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>12>a","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"TRIGONOMETRY : BEARINGS","question":"Two men P and Q set off from a base camp R prospecting for oil. P moves 20 km on a bearing of 205o and Q moves 15 km on a bearing of 060o. Calculate the    distance of Q from P (correct to the nearest whole number)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"\u2220PRQ = 90o + 25o + 30o = 145o  Using cosine rule:  r2 = q2 +  p2 - 2pqcos R  ==> r2 =  202 + 152 - 2 x 15 x 20 x cos 145o  r2 = 400 + 225 - 600 x (-cos 35o)  = 625 - 600(-0.8192)  = 625 + 491.52 = 1116.52  r = \u221a1116.52  \u2234 r = 33.41 = 33 km (to nearest km)","marks":"7","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Mathematics>1996>PART II>12>b","subject":"Mathematics","year":"1996","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"TRIGONOMETRY : BEARINGS","question":"Two men P and Q set off from a base camp R prospecting for oil. P moves 20 km on a bearing of 205o and Q moves 15 km on a bearing of 060o. Calculate the  bearing of Q from P (correct to the nearest whole number)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"sin\u2220QPR15=sin14533.41  sin\u2220QPR=15sin14533.41  sin\u2220QPR=15 \u00d7 0.573633.41=0.2575  \u2220QPR = 14.92\u00b0    \u2234 Bearing of Q from P = 25\u00b0 + 14.92\u00b0 = 39.92\u00b0 \u224a 40\u00b0 (to nearest whole number)","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"}];